---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Australian Home Collective"
  description="Australian Home Collective publishes straightforward guides for Australian households choosing products and working through problems around the home."
>
  <header class="page-intro">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
      <h1>About Australian Home Collective</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Australian Home Collective helps Australian households make more considered choices
        about the things they bring into the home.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>
  <section class="content narrow">
    <p>
      We write about the decisions that come before a purchase. Instead of beginning with a
      product list, we look at the room, the problem and the routine the item has to support.
    </p>
    <p>
      Home purchases often disappoint for ordinary reasons: the item does not fit, cannot be
      cleaned properly, gets in the way or solves a problem the household did not really have.
    </p>
    <p>
      A few checks beforehand can save money and leave the room easier to live with.
    </p>

    <h2>What the site covers</h2>
    <p>
      The main sections cover:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>kitchens and pantries</li>
      <li>laundries and bathrooms</li>
      <li>bedrooms and shared living rooms</li>
      <li>home offices</li>
      <li>garages and outdoor areas</li>
      <li>pets, nurseries and family routines</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The site is for people who want to understand the trade-offs before spending money on
      the home.
    </p>

    <h2>Our approach</h2>
    <p>
      Depending on the subject, a guide may look at:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>what to measure</li>
      <li>what to check</li>
      <li>common mistakes to avoid</li>
      <li>limits that come with renting</li>
      <li>cleaning and maintenance issues</li>
      <li>household suitability</li>
      <li>when not to buy anything yet</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      A product can look convincing online and still be wrong for a particular home.
      Measurements, layout, habits and upkeep often tell you more than the product photo.
    </p>

    <h2>How to read our guides</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective does not claim to personally test every product mentioned
      unless an article clearly says so.
    </p>
    <p>
      When a guide discusses a product type, it explains where that item may help, how much
      room it needs and where it commonly causes trouble.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this matters</h2>
    <p>
      A good home guide should help readers avoid a poor purchase and recognise when they
      already have enough.
    </p>
    <p>
      Sometimes the best answer is to measure first. Sometimes it is to clear duplicates.
      Sometimes it is to choose a removable option for a rental. Sometimes it is not to buy
      anything yet.
    </p>
    <p>
      Those are the decisions Australian Home Collective is here to help with.
    </p>

    <p>
      You can also read more about <a href="/editorial-standards/">our editorial policy</a>,
      {" "}<a href="/how-we-select-products/">how we develop recommendations</a>,
      {" "}<a href="/corrections-content-review-policy/">how we handle corrections</a> and
      {" "}<a href="/our-approach/">our before-you-buy approach</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="small">
      Images and written content on this site are owned by Australian Home Collective unless
      otherwise stated.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
